The paper deals with decoding of error-correcting codes, specifically $\ell$-Interleaved Gabidulin codes. This falls under the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The algorithm used for decoding involves row reduction of skew polynomial matrices, which is a topic in linear algebra and computational complexity, making the paper relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) and complexity theory (cs.CC) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of matrix multiplication exponent in the decoding algorithm, which is a topic in systems and control theory (cs.SY). Finally, the paper presents an improvement in the exponent of $n$ compared to previous results, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and optimization (cs.OH).
